~ teach_basics
starfish: Let's start with [b]creating a tuple[/b]. The syntax is simple: put your items inside parentheses, separated by commas.
starfish: Here's an example: [b]inventory = ('sword', 'potion', 'shield')[/b]
starfish: This creates a tuple with three items. Once created, you cannot change what's inside‚Äîno adding a fourth item, no removing the sword. It's locked!
starfish: To access items, use [b]indexing[/b] just like with lists. Remember, counting starts at 0!
starfish: [b]inventory[0][/b] gives you 'sword', [b]inventory[1][/b] gives you 'potion', and [b]inventory[2][/b] gives you 'shield'.
starfish: Want to understand why tuples can't be changed?
- Yes, explain immutability => teach_immutability
