~ teach_immutability
starfish: The word for "can't be changed" is [b]immutability[/b]. Once a tuple is created, it's frozen forever. This might seem limiting, but it's actually a superpower!
starfish: Immutability means your data is [b]protected from accidents[/b]. If you pass a tuple to a function, you know it won't be modified. If you store quest requirements as a tuple, they can't be accidentally altered.
starfish: Lists use square brackets [] and CAN be changed. Tuples use parentheses () and CANNOT be changed. Choose wisely based on what you need!
starfish: Try this in your head: [b]items = ('key', 'map')[/b]. If you try [b]items[0] = 'compass'[/b], Python will give you an error because tuples are immutable.
starfish: This protection makes your code safer and faster. Python can optimize tuples better because they never change!
- That makes sense! Continue ‚ûú => teach_unpacking


~ teach_unpacking
starfish: Here's where tuples get really cool: [b]unpacking[/b]. This lets you take a tuple's values and assign them to multiple variables at once!
starfish: Imagine you have coordinates: [b]position = (150, 200, 5)[/b] representing x, y, and floor level.
starfish: Instead of writing:[br][b]x = position[0][/b][br][b]y = position[1][/b][br][b]floor = position[2][/b]
starfish: You can simply write: [b]x, y, floor = position[/b]
starfish: Python automatically takes each value from the tuple and assigns it to the matching variable. Much cleaner!
starfish: The number of variables must match the number of items in the tuple, or Python will complain. Three items means three variables!
- Show me a real example ‚ûú => teach_example


~ teach_example
starfish: Here's a complete example using tuple unpacking in a game scenario:
starfish: [b]boss_location = (150, 200, 5)[/b][br][b]x, y, floor = boss_location[/b][br][b]print(f'Dragon at X: {x}, Y: {y}, Floor: {floor}')[/b]
starfish: This prints: [b]Dragon at X: 150, Y: 200, Floor: 5[/b]
starfish: Unpacking makes your code readable and elegant. It's commonly used when functions return multiple values!
starfish: Ready to learn some useful tuple operations?
- Yes, show me! => teach_operations


~ teach_operations
starfish: Tuples have some handy built-in operations. Let's explore the most useful ones!
starfish: [b]len(tuple)[/b] tells you how many items are in a tuple. For example: [b]party = ('Knight', 'Wizard', 'Archer')[/b] and [b]len(party)[/b] gives you 3.
starfish: You can loop through tuples just like lists: [b]for hero in party:[/b][br]->[b]print(hero)[/b]
starfish: This prints each hero's name on a separate line. Simple and powerful!
starfish: Check if an item exists: [b]'Knight' in party[/b] returns True, while [b]'Dragon' in party[/b] returns False.
starfish: You can also combine tuples with [b]+[/b]: [b]warriors = ('Knight',)[/b] and [b]mages = ('Wizard',)[/b] then [b]party = warriors + mages[/b] creates a new tuple with both!
- What about that comma after 'Knight'? => teach_single_item
