~ teach_single_item
starfish: Great catch! For a [b]single-item tuple[/b], you MUST include a comma after the item, even if it looks weird.
starfish: [b]Wrong:[/b] warriors = ('Knight') ‚Äî this is just a string in parentheses, not a tuple!
starfish: [b]Correct:[/b] warriors = ('Knight',) ‚Äî the comma tells Python "this is a tuple with one item."
starfish: Without the comma, Python thinks you're just using parentheses for grouping, like in math: (5 + 3).
starfish: It's a quirky Python rule, but once you know it, you'll never forget!
